After the discussion with [~tsugawa] and [~sjones] we found the issue is from our non-AWS compatible use of VPCs for ELB. To summarize --
1) In VPC mode, an ELB VM has 2 interfaces -- primary interface for system VPC and secondary interface for user VPC. User VPC is where the backend VMs are placed and cross-zone VM is not reachable.
2) Default route of the guest OS is through primary interface. This is necessary for internal ELB where the required endpoints (EUCA services, NTP) are on Internet.
3) The backend VMs in the same subnet (i.e., AZ) is reachable because there is a route rule by which the destination IPs in the subnet goes through the secondary interface.

{code:java}
    10.0.0.0        0.0.0.0         255.255.255.0   U     100    0        0 eth1
{code}

4) The backend VMs in the different subnet of the same VPC is not reachable because the destination IP is not in the route rule and default route through primary interface is chosen.
5) The proposed solution is to add a route rule in the ELB VMs (by ELB servo) so that all traffics bound to the user VPC goes through the secondary interface. For example, adding this rule solves the problem in the ticket.

{code:java}
   [root@euca-192-168-63-142 cloud-user]# ip route add 10.0.0.0/16 via 10.0.0.1

{code}
6) Note that the problem manifests only when 1) Cloud is in VPC, 2) ELB is across multiple AZs, 3) Cross-zone LB is enabled (off by default).
